questiontext.text:
Given that the arc length between the points \(A\) and \(B\) is \(a = {@aa@}\) and the angle between A and B is \(\theta = {@theta@}\). What is the circumference of the circle? Give your answer to the nearest whole number.

Â 

Circumference = [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]

generalfeedback.text: Recall that the arc length between two points on the circumference of a circle is given by \(a = \frac{\theta \pi r}{180^\circ}\) therefore, rearranging we get that \(r = \frac{a \cdot 180^\circ}{\theta \pi}\). Hence the radius is given by \[ r = \frac{{@aa@} \cdot 180^\circ}{{@theta@} \cdot \pi} = {@rr@}. \] Then the circumference of the circle is given by \[ C = 2 \cdot \pi \cdot r = {@ta1@}. \]
